SYPHILIS - USA: (ALABAMA)
*************************

A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Mon 14 Nov 2011
Source: WKRG.com [edited]
http://www2.wkrg.com/news/2011/nov/14/syphilis-outbreak-baldwin-county-ar-2704819/


A giant billboard on US Highway 59 carries a message that is hard to
miss. [A picture of the billboard can be found at
http://www2.wkrg.com/news/2011/nov/14/syphilis-outbreak-baldwin-county-ar-2704819/.
The billboard refers to cases of syphilis in Baldwin County, Alabama.]
"We had one syphilis case in all of 2010 and so far this year we've
had about 45 cases," according to Victor Creagh with the Alabama
Department of Public Health.

State health department officials have tracked the increase to 2 main
causes. "Escambia County, Florida that's one of the connections that
we've made and there is also pretty good involvement of drug use,
particularly crack cocaine," says Creagh. Escambia County, Florida is
dealing with its own outbreak. The highest number of reported cases in
30 years.

The treatment for syphilis is relatively simple. A shot of penicillin.
Not treating the disease can be deadly. "After many, many years of
having syphilis you can be exposed to neurosyphilis when it goes into
the CSF [cerebrospinal fluid]. Yes, it can be deadly." Dr Yolanda
Jones says syphilis is not necessarily transmitted sexually. "If you
touch someone who has syphilis or an open sore you can be exposed to
syphilis."

The billboard went up earlier this month [November 2011]. The message
is already paying off. "We had an individual to come in as a result of
seeing that billboard because he had the same symptoms in his hands
and feet." Testing and treatment for syphilis can be done for free at
any county health department.

[Byline: Debbie Williams]

